Q: How to create WinUI3 GUI in PowerShell? A: <p>I think perhaps there could be a better way to manage DLLS instead of doing it manually.</p>
<p>The Nuget package can be installed by using the PSResource management of Powershell, and DLLs can be retrieved and managed through automatic scanning.</p>
<pre class="lang-bash prettyprint-override"><code>$NuPackList = @(
    'Microsoft.Windows.SDK.NET.Ref'
    &quot;Microsoft.Graphics.Win2D&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.WinUI&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.Base&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.Foundation&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.InteractiveExperiences&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.Runtime&quot;
    &quot;Microsoft.WindowsAppSDK.DWrite&quot;
)

Register-PSResourceRepository -Name 'NuGetGallery' -Uri 'https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json'
foreach($Pack in $NuPackList){
    Install-PSResource -Repository 'NuGetGallery' -Name $Pack -Scope 'CurrentUser' -SkipDependencyCheck -TrustRepository
}
</code></pre>
<p>With these codes, you can use Powershell to install the Nuget packages you need. Note that this approach cannot manage dependencies. You need to list the dependent items by yourself. The simplest way is to open a WinUI3 template project and check the dependencies of the Nuget package within it.</p>
<p>You can automatically retrieve and load DLLS through the following code.</p>
<pre class="lang-bash prettyprint-override"><code>$PackDirs = Get-InstalledPSResource -Name $NuPackList -Scope 'CurrentUser' |
Sort-Object -Top $NuPackList.Count -Property @{ Expression = { [version] $_.Version } ; Descending = $true } |
ForEach-Object { &quot;$($_.InstalledLocation)\$($_.Name)\$($_.Version)&quot; }

foreach ($Dir in $PackDirs) {
    if (Test-Path -Path (Join-Path $Dir 'runtimes') -PathType Container) {
        $Env:Path += &quot;;$(Join-Path $Dir 'runtimes' 'win-x64' 'native')&quot;
    }
    if (Test-Path -Path (Join-Path $Dir 'runtimes-framework') -PathType Container) {
        $Env:Path += &quot;;$(Join-Path $Dir 'runtimes-framework' 'win-x64' 'native')&quot;
    }
}

$DllFilters = Get-InstalledPSResource -Name $NuPackList -Scope 'CurrentUser' |
Sort-Object -Top $NuPackList.Count -Property @{ Expression = { [version] $_.Version } ; Descending = $true } |
ForEach-Object { &quot;$($_.InstalledLocation)\$($_.Name)\$($_.Version)\lib\*.dll&quot; }

$Dlls = $DllFilters | Get-ChildItem -Recurse -File -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object { $_.FullName }

[string[]]$Dlls = $Dlls + @(
    &lt;#&quot;PresentationFramework&quot;
    &quot;PresentationCore&quot;
    &quot;InteropCompositor&quot;#&gt;
    &quot;System.Drawing&quot;
    &quot;System.Numerics.Vectors&quot;
    &quot;System.Linq&quot;
    &quot;System.Console&quot;
    &quot;System.Management.Automation&quot;
)

$DllSet = [System.Collections.Generic.HashSet[string]]::new()
foreach ($Dll in $Dlls) {
    $Name = $Dll.Split(&quot;\&quot;)[-1] -replace '.dll$', ''
    if ($DllSet.Contains($Name)) {
        continue
    }
    [void]$DllSet.Add($Name)
    try {
        Add-Type -AssemblyName $Dll
    }
    catch {
        Write-Host &quot;$Dll 加载失败: $_&quot;
    }
}
</code></pre>

Q: Volley JsonObjectRequest Error response A: <p>As I see here your response is in JsonArray format.
So try with <code>JsonArrayRequest </code></p>
<pre><code>private void getBeerDetails() {
    JsonArrayRequest jsonObjectRequest = new JsonArrayRequest 
            (Request.Method.GET,
                    &quot;https://api.punkapi.com/v2/beers/13&quot;,
                    null, new Response.Listener&lt;JSONArray&gt;() {

                @Override
                public void onResponse(JSONArray response) {

                       if(response.length()&gt;0){
                           //make a loop and add item to your list
                           }
                }
            }, new Response.ErrorListener() {

                @Override
                public void onErrorResponse(VolleyError error) {
                    VolleyLog.d(&quot;Error:&quot;, error.getMessage());
                }
            });

    requestQueue.add(jsonObjectRequest);
}
</code></pre>

Q: Laravel route ignore locale parameter A: <p>Use <code>$request-&gt;route()-&gt;forgetParameter('locale');</code> in the middleware.</p>
<p>In your case it will look like this</p>
<pre><code>public function handle($request, Closure $next)
{
    $locale = $request-&gt;segment(1);
    session(['locale' =&gt; $locale]);
    app()-&gt;setLocale($locale);

    $request-&gt;route()-&gt;forgetParameter('lang');

    return $next($request);
}
</code></pre>
<p>P.S. keep in mind in your code you are using <code>{lang}</code> instead of <code>{locale}</code></p>

Q: How to use ReplaceToken-filter with properties and Gradle 9 Configuration Cache A: <p>If you want a strongly‑typed, re‑usable solution, expose <code>foo</code> from a convention plugin as a <code>Property&lt;String&gt;</code> and wire it to <code>ProcessResources</code> in each project.The key is that <strong>the extension must hold only values/Providers, not a <code>Project</code> instance</strong>.</p>
<pre><code>
import org.gradle.api.Plugin
import org.gradle.api.Project
import org.gradle.api.provider.Provider

abstract class FooConventions : Plugin&lt;Project&gt; {
    override fun apply(project: Project) {
        // Extension that exposes a typed property
        val fooExt = project.extensions.create(&quot;fooExt&quot;, FooExtension::class.java)

        // Compute foo as Provider&lt;String&gt;
        val foo: Provider&lt;String&gt; = project.providers
            .gradleProperty(&quot;foo&quot;)
            .orElse(project.providers.gradleProperty(&quot;defaultFoo&quot;))

        // Do not store Project on the extension; store only values/Property/Provider
        fooExt.foo.set(foo)

        // Configure tasks cache-safely
        project.tasks.withType(org.gradle.language.jvm.tasks.ProcessResources::class.java).configureEach {
            inputs.property(&quot;foo&quot;, fooExt.foo)
            filesMatching(&quot;merry-xmas&quot;) {
                val tokens = mapOf(&quot;andAHappyNewYear&quot; to fooExt.foo.get())
                filter(org.apache.tools.ant.filters.ReplaceTokens::class.java, mapOf(&quot;tokens&quot; to tokens))
            }
        }
    }
}

abstract class FooExtension @javax.inject.Inject constructor(
    objects: org.gradle.api.model.ObjectFactory
) {
    val foo: org.gradle.api.provider.Property&lt;String&gt; = objects.property(String::class.java)
}
``
</code></pre>
<p>Kindly apply the plugin to your subprojects and you’re done. Because the extension holds only a <code>Property&lt;String&gt;</code>, the configuration cache can serialize it. No Gradle model types are captured in task actions/inputs. Kindly read <a href="https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/configuration_cache_requirements.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Gradle Documentation</a>.</p>
<p>rootProject.properties[...] / <code>extra[&quot;foo&quot;]</code> in task inputs only captures parts of the <code>Project</code> object and leads to <code>&quot;cannot serialize object of type 'org.gradle.api.internal.project.DefaultProject'&quot;</code> with the configuration cache. Declare a <code>Property&lt;String&gt;</code> or use a <code>Provider&lt;String&gt;</code> instead. Register only concrete values, <code>Provider</code>, <code>Property</code>, or <code>FileCollection</code> at execution time.</p>

Q: Is there any way to modify `req.query` in Express v5? A: <p>How about just replacing the fields of <code>query</code> and <code>params</code> ? This is a solution after discussion with GPT.</p>
<pre><code>import httpStatus from 'http-status';
import ApiError from '../utils/ApiError';
import { NextFunction, Request, Response } from 'express';
import pick from '../utils/pick';
import Joi from 'joi';

const validate = (schema: object) =&gt; (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) =&gt; {
  const validSchema = pick(schema, ['params', 'query', 'body']);
  const obj = pick(req, Object.keys(validSchema));
  const { value, error } = Joi.compile(validSchema)
    .prefs({ errors: { label: 'key' }, abortEarly: false })
    .validate(obj);
  if (error) {
    const errorMessage = error.details.map((details) =&gt; details.message).join(', ');
    return next(new ApiError(httpStatus.BAD_REQUEST, errorMessage));
  }

  // Here we are not assigning `req.query` directly.
  // Express v5 exposes it as a getter-only property.
  // Instead, mutate existing objects.
  const replaceObject = (target: unknown, source: unknown) =&gt; {
    if (!target || typeof target !== 'object' || !source || typeof source !== 'object') return;
    for (const key of Object.keys(target as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;)) {
      delete (target as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;)[key];
    }
    Object.assign(target as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;, source as Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;);
  };

  if ((value as any).params) replaceObject(req.params, (value as any).params);
  if ((value as any).query) replaceObject(req.query, (value as any).query);
  if ((value as any).body) replaceObject(req.body, (value as any).body);

  return next();
};
</code></pre>
